--- /dev/null
+++ b/docs/ffmpeg-rkmpp-backend.md
@@ -0,0 +1,208 @@
+# FFmpeg / `h264_rkmpp` encode-session backend
+
+A narrow, fail-closed FFmpeg encode backend for GNOME Remote Desktop, targeting
+the Rockchip RK3588 (`h264_rkmpp`). It is a sibling of the existing VA-API
+backend (`grd-encode-session-vaapi.c`), not a generic user-selectable encoder
+zoo.
+
+## Scope (deliberately narrow)
+
+* **H.264 only**, AVC420 only (no AVC444v2 yet).
+* **`h264_rkmpp` hard-whitelisted** — the encoder is looked up by name; nothing
+  else is accepted.
+* **Zero-copy only** — input frames are handed to the encoder as
+  `AV_PIX_FMT_DRM_PRIME` (`AVDRMFrameDescriptor`). NV12, `DRM_FORMAT_MOD_LINEAR`.
+* **Low-latency only** — no B-frames, single reference, `AV_CODEC_FLAG_LOW_DELAY`,
+  fixed QP where the encoder supports it (see D3).
+* **Fail closed** — if any of {encoder present, encoder opens with our settings,
+  no B-frames, zero-copy DRM-PRIME import actually works} cannot be guaranteed,
+  the session **declines** (returns `NULL`) and GRD falls through to the
+  already-preferred VA-API path (tried first) and then RFX. It never produces a
+  degraded (copy-based or non-low-latency) session.
+* **VA-API stays preferred.** FFmpeg is probed only *after* VA-API and only when
+  VA-API did not produce a session.
+
+## Pipeline (where this slots in)
+
+```
+capture ─▶ Vulkan RGB→NV12 compute (grd-rdp-view-creator-avc)
+            │   writes NV12 into a pool surface (GrdImageViewNV12)
+            ▼
+        grd-encode-session-ffmpeg   ── encode_frame()  [renderer thread]
+            │                           builds AVDRMFrameDescriptor, queues AVFrame
+            │                        ── lock_bitstream() [base encode thread]
+            │                           avcodec_send_frame + avcodec_receive_packet
+            ▼
+        GrdBitstream (Annex-B) + GrdAVCFrameInfo ─▶ RDPGFX AVC420
+```
+
+The encode-session contract is six vfuncs (`grd-encode-session.h:40-54`):
+`get_surface_size`, `get_image_views`, `has_pending_frames`, `encode_frame`,
+`lock_bitstream`, `unlock_bitstream`.
+
+## Key design decisions
+
+### D1 — GBM allocates the NV12 surfaces (not Vulkan, not VA-API, not dma-heap)
+
+The VA-API backend works because *VA-API* allocates the NV12 surface and exports
+it as a dma-buf, which Vulkan then imports. There is **no VkImage→dma-buf export
+path in the tree** (`grd_vk_dma_buf_image_new` is import-only;
+`vkGetMemoryFdKHR` is not wired), and MPP imports an externally-owned fd rather
+than allocating for us. So GRD must own the allocation.
+
+We allocate the NV12 buffer with **GBM on the DRM render node**, then import the
+*same* dma-buf fd into **both**:
+* Vulkan, via the existing `grd_vk_dma_buf_image_new` (Y as `R8_UNORM`, UV as
+  `R8G8_UNORM`), so the compute shader can write NV12 into it; and
+* MPP, via an `AVDRMFrameDescriptor`, for zero-copy encode.
+
+This mirrors VA-API's "external allocator owns, both sides import" pattern with
+minimal new code.
+
+*Why GBM and not dma-heap:* on the target board `/dev/dma_heap/*` is
+root-only (`crw-------`), while the render node carries a render-group ACL
+(`crw-rw----+`) that the daemon already uses for Vulkan/VA-API. GBM allocates on
+the render node, so it respects existing permissions, is guaranteed importable by
+the same-GPU Vulkan driver, and reports the real plane strides/offsets/modifier.
+
+### D2 — `DRM_FORMAT_MOD_LINEAR`, single source of truth for strides
+
+The buffer is forced linear (`GBM_BO_USE_LINEAR`). The per-plane `offset`,
+`pitch` and `modifier` come straight from GBM
+(`gbm_bo_get_offset` / `gbm_bo_get_stride_for_plane` / `gbm_bo_get_modifier`) and
+are used verbatim for *both* the Vulkan import and the MPP descriptor — so the two
+importers can never disagree on layout. MPP back-derives
+`ver_stride = planes[1].offset / planes[0].pitch`; because both planes use GBM's
+real values this is consistent by construction. Anything non-linear fails the
+Vulkan import and declines.
+
+### D3 — Fixed QP 22 (mirror VA-API), portable across both rkmpp encoders
+
+There are **two independent `h264_rkmpp` encoder implementations** with divergent
+option sets, and the backend must work on both:
+
+* **ffmpeg-rockchip** (nyanmisaka) — the long-standing fork. Has a fixed-QP
+  rate-control mode (its `rc_mode` constant is spelled **`CQP`** →
+  `MPP_ENC_RC_MODE_FIXQP`) and a `qp_init` option; with the mode left at its
+  default it auto-selects fixed QP as soon as `qp_init >= 0`.
+* **mainline FFmpeg** (`libavcodec/rkmppenc.c`, merged 2025-10, first released in
+  8.1) — has **no fixed-QP mode** (only `rc` = vbr/cbr/avbr) and **no `qp_init`**.
+
+VA-API uses `VA_RC_CQP` with `pic_init_qp = 22` and reports `qp = 22`,
+`quality = 100` in `GrdAVCFrameInfo`. We mirror the *reported* constants and steer
+the encoder to constant quality portably by setting **only `qp_init = 22`** and
+**never naming the rate-control mode**. Naming it is unsafe: passing an invalid
+value for a *known* option makes `avcodec_open2()` fail outright
+(`av_opt_set_dict2` returns `EINVAL`, not "ignored") — which is exactly what the
+old `rc_mode=fixqp` did on ffmpeg-rockchip, whose fixed-QP value is `CQP`, not
+`fixqp`. `qp_init` is unknown on mainline, so it is harmlessly ignored there. For
+mainline, which cannot do fixed QP, we additionally set a **fallback `bit_rate`**
+(~0.1 bits·pixel⁻¹·frame⁻¹, capped at 100 Mbit/s) so its VBR mode produces a sane
+stream; ffmpeg-rockchip ignores `bit_rate` in fixed-QP mode.
+
+`AV_CODEC_FLAG_LOW_DELAY` is also load-bearing here: without it ffmpeg-rockchip
+encodes asynchronously (buffering ~4 frames), which would break the strict
+1-in-1-out `lock_bitstream` model; with it the encoder blocks for each frame's
+packet. Mainline is 1-in-1-out regardless.
+
+### D4 — Threading: all `AVCodecContext` access on one thread
+
+The base class calls `lock_bitstream` on a dedicated encode thread while
+`encode_frame`/`unlock_bitstream` run on the renderer thread. FFmpeg forbids
+concurrent use of one `AVCodecContext`. So:
+* `encode_frame` (renderer thread) only builds the `AVFrame` (DRM descriptor from
+  the surface — no `avctx` access) and stashes it in a pending map.
+* `lock_bitstream` (encode thread) does **both** `avcodec_send_frame` and
+  `avcodec_receive_packet`.
+* `unlock_bitstream` (renderer thread) only frees the owned `AVPacket`.
+
+Two mutexes guard the pending-frames and bitstreams maps; no `avctx` mutex is
+needed. Because the encoder has no reordering (no B-frames, single ref) and the
+base class drains locks FIFO, output order == submission order.
+
+### D5 — Single initial IDR, then P-frames (mirror VA-API), validated by a smoke encode
+
+The first frame is forced to IDR; the rest are P-frames with an effectively
+infinite GOP. Client refresh is driven by render-context recreation (a new
+session ⇒ a new IDR), exactly as with VA-API.
+
+`grd_encode_session_ffmpeg_new` runs a **start-of-session smoke encode**: it
+imports one real GBM dma-buf and runs one `send_frame`+`receive_packet`. If that
+fails (e.g. `h264_rkmpp` present but `/dev/mpp_service` missing, or DRM-PRIME
+import rejected) the session declines — this is the definitive zero-copy gate.
+The throwaway packet is dropped and the next (first real) frame is forced to IDR
+so the client's stream starts clean.
+
+### D6 — Fail-closed gates (all in `grd_encode_session_ffmpeg_new`)
+
+1. `avcodec_find_encoder_by_name("h264_rkmpp")` is `NULL` ⇒ decline. (Covers
+   stock distro FFmpeg without `--enable-rkmpp`; the daemon then uses VA-API/RFX.)
+2. GBM/Vulkan surface allocation or import rejects the buffer ⇒ decline.
+3. `avcodec_open2` fails ⇒ decline.
+4. After open, `avctx->max_b_frames != 0` ⇒ decline (low-latency not honoured).
+5. Smoke encode fails ⇒ decline (zero-copy DRM-PRIME not actually working).
+
+Gate 1 also lives in `grd_hwaccel_ffmpeg_new`, so the `&& hwaccel_ffmpeg` guard
+in the selector short-circuits cleanly on machines without rkmpp.
+
+### D7 — Selection order and `vk_device` lifetime
+
+`create_hw_accelerated_encode_session` tries VA-API first, then FFmpeg, then RFX.
+`maybe_initialize_hardware_acceleration` previously destroyed `vk_device` when
+VA-API failed to initialize; that is changed so `vk_device` survives if *either*
+hardware encoder initializes — otherwise the FFmpeg path (which needs Vulkan for
+the NV12 compute) could never run on a board without VA-API.
+
+## Files
+
+* `src/grd-encode-session-ffmpeg.{c,h}` — the backend (GBM pool, Vulkan import,
+  DRM-PRIME descriptors, send/receive, gates).
+* `src/grd-hwaccel-ffmpeg.{c,h}` — thin object: gate 1, owns the GBM device on the
+  render node, creates sessions (parallels `GrdHwAccelVaapi`).
+* `src/grd-rdp-render-context.c` — `try_create_ffmpeg_session` (AVC420-only),
+  called after VA-API.
+* `src/grd-rdp-renderer.c` — create/hold/get/dispose `hwaccel_ffmpeg`; keep
+  `vk_device` alive if either encoder initialized.
+* `meson.build`, `meson_options.txt`, `config.h.meson`, `src/meson.build` —
+  `ffmpeg` feature (`auto`), `libavcodec`/`libavutil`/`gbm` deps, `HAVE_FFMPEG`.
+
+## Build & deploy
+
+```
+meson setup build -Dffmpeg=enabled
+ninja -C build
+```
+
+The `ffmpeg` feature is `auto`: it enables when `libavcodec`/`libavutil`/`gbm`
+are present. **`h264_rkmpp` (encoder) is resolved at runtime**, so the daemon
+links fine against any FFmpeg and simply declines the backend (gate 1) when the
+encoder is absent.
+
+To actually encode, the host needs an FFmpeg whose `h264_rkmpp` **encoder** is
+present (built `--enable-rkmpp`, with the Rockchip MPP userspace and a kernel
+exposing `/dev/mpp_service`). Either of:
+
+* **mainline FFmpeg ≥ 8.1** (or current `master`) — the encoder was merged
+  2025-10-07 and requires `rockchip_mpp >= 1.3.8`; or
+* **`nyanmisaka/ffmpeg-rockchip`** — the feature-rich fork (also the only option
+  on released FFmpeg ≤ 8.0, which is rkmpp **decode-only**).
+
+The backend was reconciled against both implementations' sources and is designed
+to run on either (see D3); it has not yet been runtime-tested on hardware.
+
+## On-hardware validation checklist (points that cannot be checked off-target)
+
+* Constant-quality behaviour per build — confirm ffmpeg-rockchip logs
+  `Rate Control mode is set to CQP` with QP 22 (from `qp_init`), and that mainline
+  produces a reasonably-sized VBR stream from the fallback `bit_rate`. (Option
+  names were reconciled against both sources; `qp_init` is the only AVOption set,
+  and unknown options are logged, not fatal — the smoke encode is the real gate.)
+* `hw_frames_ctx` — **mainline requires** a DRM `hw_frames_ctx` with `sw_format`
+  NV12 on DRM-PRIME input (`rkmpp_set_hw_frame` returns `EINVAL` without it); it is
+  created best-effort here, so if DRM hwcontext init fails on mainline the smoke
+  encode declines. ffmpeg-rockchip ignores the context (reads the DRM descriptor
+  directly) but needs `sw_pix_fmt` = NV12, which is set explicitly.
+* Color signalling — `color_range = MPEG` (limited); confirm it matches the
+  RGB→NV12 matrix used by `grd-rdp-view-creator-avc` if colors look off.
+* Width/height alignment — surfaces are 16-aligned (macroblock); RKVENC is happy
+  with 16. GBM stride/offset are used as-is for `hor_stride`/`ver_stride`.
